data.name: label4.Text
data.value: Streaming Mode: [Default Buffered] - Buffered: optimize commands streaming filling up grbl receive buffer [recommended] - Synchronous: wait for the execution of each command prior to send the very next command [slower but safer] - RepeatOnError: same as Synchronous but repeat commands if detect error [experimental]

data.name: label3.Text
data.value: Connection Protocol: - UsbSerial: is the most common protocol. Should be used if your engraver is connected to USB or COM port. - UsbSerial2: an alternative implementation of USB serial to bypass Microsoft SerialPort issues - Telnet: if you have a WiFi-Telnet bridge. Communication is implemented like a simple telnet client-server. - LaserWebESP8266: support WiFi connection via WebSocket. Compatible with LaserWeb-ESP8266 software.

data.name: label6.Text
data.value: Threading Mode: UltraFast, Fast, Quiet, Slow. [Default Fast] This setting affect the speed of sending thread and the frequency of status report request. Set slower values if you are experiencing issues.

data.name: label7.Text
data.value: LaserGRBL can detect issues and warn the user providing info about how to solve them. If disabled all the issues are silently managed without warning.

data.name: label2.Text
data.value: If enabled LaserGRBL send a soft-reset when the connection to grbl is opened.

data.name: label8.Text
data.value: If enabled LaserGRBL send a hard-reset when the connection to grbl is opened. [Position is lost!]

data.name: label9.Text
data.value: Firmware type - Grbl: the awesome firmware for which LaserGRBL was developed for. - Smoothie [experimental]: support has been added recently and is not fully tested. - Marlin [experimental]: support has been added recently and is not fully tested. - VigoWork [experimental]: support for VG-L7x model that is non grbl-standard.

data.name: label46.Text
data.value: In enabled LaserGRBL send a $I command and detect some information from the machine (i.e. the machine rx buffer size). Please do not disable this feature.

data.name: label1.Text
data.value: LaserGRBL use power modulation through G-Code "S command" to produce grayscale tones. Your laser must support TTL control connected to arduino PIN D11. If not, please disable PWM support.

data.name: label5.Text
data.value: By default LaserGRBL produces engraving lines in both travel directions of the laser head. Some tests have shown that this mode (which is faster) produces lower quality results. If the maximum marking quality is desired, activate this option.

data.name: label22.Text
data.value: The max resolution available in LaserGRBL is 20 lines/mm (about 500dpi) that is high enough for most user. If you need higher resolution you can enable "HiRes" and remove this limit. Be careful: LaserGRBL will need many more resources!

data.name: label39.Text
data.value:
By default LaserGRBL use G0 - rapid movement - to skip white parts of your jobs. This speed up the engraving process but it can result in inaccurate positioning with disappointing results. It is usually possible to improve the results by correctly setting the maximum acceleration and speed values ($ 120,121,122 and $ 110,111,112) in the grbl configuration.
If you disable this feature LaserGRBL will use G1 linear movement at the same job speed, with the result that all the engraving process is done at the same speed. This will slow down the process, but can drammatically improve the result where others approacs fails.

data.name: label40.Text
data.value: LaserGRBL will warn you if you are going to create a job bigger then your engraver workspace. Set this flag if you don't whant this safety control.

data.name: label10.Text
data.value:
Without "Continuous Jog" when jog button is pressed LaserGRBL send Jog request with settled speed and movement; and the jog is fully executed to the final position. If you enable "Continuous Jog" jogging is sent with mouse-down and aborted/interrupted on mouse-up, so you can do approximative positioning but in a very comfortable way.
NOTE: "Continuous Jog" only work with Grbl v1.1 or later, and require table size is correctily configured in Grbl Configuration (Menu "Grbl" -> "Grbl Configuration" $130, $131, $132)

data.name: label11.Text
data.value: LaserGRBL is not designed to support Z axis, but if you have a 3axis hardware maybe you could find this option usefull.

data.value: Time OFF: after this cooling time LaserGRBL will send a resume command to continue engraving job.

data.name: label12.Text
data.value: Some laser diodes can heat-up to much if they run for a long time at the highest power. To prevent diode overheating and increase your laser lifetime you can add some automatic cooling-down cycles that insert some pause during engraivng process. If Auto Cooling is enabled LaserGRBL will send automatic "feed hold" and "job resume" according with ON-OFF timing configuration.

data.name: label13.Text
data.value: Time ON: this is the maximum time that Laser will stay on during engraving process. After this time LaserGRBL will send an automatic feed hold to cool down the laser.

data.name: LblHeader.Text
data.value:
LaserGRBL will append this GCode before starting any job. You can customize this code, for example adding M8 to turn on fan.
Here you can use the same syntax of custom buttons if you need to push some positioning related to the specific job is going to be executed.

data.name: LblFooter.Text
data.value:
LaserGRBL will enqueue this GCode at the end of any job. Can be used to push back your engraver in a initial state like going back to zero position or sending M9 to turn off fan etc.
Here you can use the same syntax of custom buttons.

data.name: LblPasses.Text
data.value:
When performing multiple passes LaserGRBL will push this GCode in the between of each passes. Can be used to move Z down to perform deeper cuts.
Here you can use the same syntax of custom buttons.
